english:
  title: On Mengyang
  author: Lee Saek
  language: eng
  text: |-
    In the year Dingyu, after Li Zuolang passed the examination, he asked his friend Zheng Ziyun to request a courtesy name from me. I said, "Li Shu is my friend—why does he not write to me himself? This shows a failure of propriety, and I find it difficult to speak on such matters."

    I have long held Li Shu in affection. When he first attempted the civil service examination, he suddenly appeared at my home carrying his composition and asked me to review it. Seeing his appearance—majestic and his spirit luminous—my heart rejoiced. Upon reading his writing, I found it precise and substantial, unmarred by vulgarity. With only minor refinements, it remained unflawed. My joy doubled. Not long after our acquaintance, he was indeed selected by the examiners, and within a few years, he was appointed Remonstrator. His bearing outshone all others, and everyone said, "Remonstrator Li will surely rise to great position." Yet he has now served his parents in the countryside for many years without emerging, and though called to service, he does not respond—as if he has withdrawn from the world.

    Now his uncle Chen, visiting the capital, sent me a letter saying: "When Ziyun departed, we pressed him to request your courtesy name for my nephew. We, being humble folk, cannot approach a sage directly. Yet Ziyun enjoys your favor, and through him we hope to receive your words—what an honor that would be! We did not pause to consider propriety in our boldness. If you will not despise us, please reveal to us the reason such a request cannot be granted, that we might learn."

    I replied: "Shu means the work of yang—the spring breath unfolds, all things flourish and bloom. Great harmony flows and penetrates everywhere without separation. This is like the age of Yao and Shun in this world. In such times, ruler and minister are equally sage, rites and music flourish greatly, and the vicious are mere wisps upon the azure sky. As that era departed, the sun reached its zenith, its brilliance most dazzling—such was the height of its transformative power and virtue.

    Now, those with even slight learning say: 'What man was Shun, and what man am I?' If Li Shu does not aspire to the age of Yao and Shun, I cannot believe it. Thus I name him Mengyang. Let Mengyang embody this name and courtesy name through his deeds. Should one say, 'My name means withdrawal, signifying contraction,' then one approaches the way of Laozi—this is yin, not yang. Yang is the way of the gentleman. I urge us to strive together."
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Dingyu year refers to 1357 in the lunar calendar, during the late Goryeo period.
  - key: ''
    value: The Four Villains (四凶) were legendary malevolent figures in ancient Chinese mythology, representing chaos and disorder.
  - key: ''
    value: Yao and Shun represent the golden age of sage-kings in Confucian tradition, embodying perfect virtue and rule.
  - key: ''
    value: The courtesy name 'Mengyang' (孟陽) combines 'Meng' (孟), meaning first or primary, with 'Yang' (陽), meaning brightness or the masculine principle, thus suggesting 'primordial brightness' or the active manifestation of virtue.
